        <body>
            <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" resp="#NW">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><g ref="#feathermark"/>ᚂᚂᚂᚃᚃᚃᚃᚂᚂᚂᚂᚃᚃᚃᚂ
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:space="preserve" resp="#NW">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><g ref="#feathermark"/>LLLVVVVLLLLVVVL
                </ab>
                <ab type="list">᚛LLLVVVVLLLLVVVL</ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1"><note>The proposed reading starts from a possible feather-mark, reading towards the wrist guard/handle (L-R if holding sword horizontally in right hand) and takes the scores to be letters of the B aicme.</note></app>
                 <app n="2"><note>Read in the opposite direction, the strokes look like letters of the H aicme: DTTTDDDDTTTTDDD᚜ (Raftery 1969, 162).</note></app> 
                </listApp>
            </div>
           <!-- <div type="translation">
                <p></p>
            </div>-->
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The arrangement of the elements – a stem-line, a feather-mark and strokes – relative to each other has the formal characteristics of an ogham inscription, but it lacks the substance for a real text – namely a human language utterance that would naturally entail much greater variation in the choice of alphabetic characters. The strokes are only to one side of the stem-line and thus only correspond to the B or to the H aicme, and they represent only two of the five possible characters within each aicme, unless the very number of identical characters in immediate sequence carries information. The notches are probably to be regarded as para-ogham, i.e. a system of notation inspired by the lay-out of ogham inscriptions, but not encoding language. The strokes are an ogham-like code, but not a text in ogham. Perhaps they designate a weaving pattern.</p>                
            </div>
